    "discriminators": [
     "An ARC SUSTAINS. It is the only ELECTRICITY subcategory whose core is a continuous noise bed rather than an event: a Jacob's ladder or a welding arc holds a rough broadband roar for seconds, often ridden by a 50/60 Hz buzz component.",
     "Against ELECZap: an arc is an order of magnitude longer with a much lower crest factor — energy is held, not spent in one impulse.",
     "Against ELECSprk: sparks are a train of resolvable discrete crackles (high transient_count, high onset_rate). An arc's noise is continuous — few resolvable onsets, higher stationarity.",
     "Against ELECBuzz: an arc is NOISE (spectral_flatness ~0.55, low harmonicity); a hum is a harmonic COMB (flatness < 0.2, harmonicity > 0.6). This is the sharpest single test in the category.",
     "Against COMStatic: an arc is less stationary and less flat than pure electronic static, and usually shows a low-frequency mains component that static lacks."
    ],
    "confusable_with": [
     "ELECZap",
     "ELECSprk",
     "ELECBuzz",
     "ELECMisc",
     "COMStatic"
    ]
   }
