    "discriminators": [
     "A STOCHASTIC CRACKLE TRAIN. Sparks are many bright micro-impulses per second arriving at IRREGULAR, unpredictable intervals. The signature is a conjunction and neither half works alone: HIGH onset_rate_per_second TOGETHER WITH LOW onset_periodicity.",
     "Against ELECZap — this is the load-bearing rule of the category, and it is a REPETITION-RATE rule. UCS states both halves of it explicitly: 'a singular spark would probably be a ZAP', and (under ZAP) 'a taser is a series of ZAPS'. So COUNT and REGULARITY decide, not timbre. A ZAP is ONE impulse, or a SMALL number of them fired in a REGULAR volley (a taser's pulse train: onset_periodicity HIGH, typically 10-40 pulses/s). SPARKS are MANY impulses at an IRREGULAR rate (onset_periodicity < 0.3). Rate alone is ambiguous — a taser and a sparkler can both fire 20 events/second. Rate AND periodicity together are decisive.",
     "Against ELECArc: an arc is continuous noise with few resolvable onsets and high stationarity; sparks resolve into countable crackles (high transient_count, high crest_factor, high envelope_kurtosis).",
     "Against FIRECrkl: near-identical morphology, and a genuine failure mode. Electrical sparks sit HIGHER (spectral_centroid ~4-6 kHz, almost no low-band energy) and are drier; fire crackle carries a broadband combustion roar underneath (higher low_band_energy, higher stationarity). Text must break ties.",
     "A sparkler, a welding spatter, or a downed line arcing to ground is the canonical case."
    ],
